\textbf{42.} \\

\textbf{Breakdown of the expression:} The expression is a conjunction of three disjunctions: 
\begin{itemize}
    \item First disjunction: \( p \lor \neg q \) 
    \item Second disjunction: \( q \lor \neg r \) 
    \item Third disjunction: \( r \lor \neg p \) 
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Case 1:} \( p \), \( q \), and \( r \) are all true: \\

\( p \) is true: \( p \lor \neg q \) becomes \( T \lor \neg T = T \lor F = T \). \\

\( q \) is true: \( q \lor \neg r \) becomes \( T \lor \neg T = T \lor F = T \). \\

\( r \) is true: \( r \lor \neg p \) becomes \( T \lor \neg T = T \lor F = T \). \\

Since all three disjunctions are true, the entire conjunction is true. \\

\textbf{Case 2:} \( p \), \( q \), and \( r \) are all false: \\

\( p \) is false: \( p \lor \neg q \) becomes \( F \lor \neg F = F \lor T = T \). \\

\( q \) is false: \( q \lor \neg r \) becomes \( F \lor \neg F = F \lor T = T \). \\

\( r \) is false: \( r \lor \neg p \) becomes \( F \lor \neg F = F \lor T = T \). \\

Again, since all three disjunctions are true, the entire conjunction is true. \\

\textbf{Case 3:} One or more of \( p \), \( q \), and \( r \) have different truth values: \\

Without loss of generality, consider the case where \( p \) is true, \( q \) is false, and \( r \) is false: \\

\( p \lor \neg q \) becomes \( T \lor T = T \) (true). \\

\( q \lor \neg r \) becomes \( F \lor T = T \) (true). \\

\( r \lor \neg p \) becomes \( F \lor F = F \) (false). \\

Since at least one of the disjunctions is false, the entire conjunction is false. \\

\textbf{Conclusion:} \\

The expression \( (p \lor \neg q) \land (q \lor \neg r) \land (r \lor \neg p) \) evaluates to true when \( p \), \( q \), and \( r \) have the same truth value (either all true or all false) because all disjunctions will be true. When \( p \), \( q \), and \( r \) have different truth values, at least one disjunction will be false, leading the entire conjunction to be false. Thus, the original expression is true if and only if \( p \), \( q \), and \( r \) share the same truth value. \\

\textbf{43.} \\

\textbf{Breakdown of the expression:} The expression consists of two main parts combined by a conjunction (\( \land \)): 
\begin{itemize}
    \item First part: \( p \lor q \lor r \) (at least one of \( p \), \( q \), or \( r \) is true) 
    \item Second part: \( \neg p \lor \neg q \lor \neg r \) (at least one of \( p \), \( q \), or \( r \) is false) 
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Case 1:} At least one of \( p \), \( q \), or \( r \) is true, and at least one is false. \\

If at least one of the variables is true, then \( p \lor q \lor r \) will evaluate to true. \\

If at least one of the variables is false, then at least one of \( \neg p \), \( \neg q \), or \( \neg r \) will be true, making \( \neg p \lor \neg q \lor \neg r \) evaluate to true as well. \\

Since both parts of the conjunction are true in this case, the overall expression \( (p \lor q \lor r) \land (\neg p \lor \neg q \lor \neg r) \) is true. \\

\textbf{Case 2:} All three variables have the same truth value. \\

1. If all three are true: \( p \lor q \lor r \) evaluates to true because all variables are true. \( \neg p \lor \neg q \lor \neg r \) evaluates to false because all variables are false, resulting in \( \neg p \), \( \neg q \), and \( \neg r \) being false. \\

In this scenario, since the first part is true and the second part is false, the overall expression is false. \\

2. If all three are false: \( p \lor q \lor r \) evaluates to false because all variables are false. \( \neg p \lor \neg q \lor \neg r \) evaluates to true because all variables are false, making \( \neg p \), \( \neg q \), and \( \neg r \) true. \\

In this case, since the first part is false and the second part is true, the overall expression is false. \\

\textbf{Conclusion:} \\

Thus, the expression \( (p \lor q \lor r) \land (\neg p \lor \neg q \lor \neg r) \) is true when at least one of \( p \), \( q \), or \( r \) is true and at least one is false because both parts of the conjunction are satisfied. However, when all three variables share the same truth value—whether true or false—one part will be true while the other will be false, resulting in the entire expression being false. \\
