Sounds like Russell's paradox(we had already read that in Grade-09, Higher-Math book). This scenario is a classic example of a paradox, specifically known as the barber paradox.

\begin{itemize}
    \item Definition: The barber shaves those people who do not shave themselves.
\end{itemize}

Two possibilities arise when considering whether the barber shaves himself:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item If the barber shaves himself: According to the legend, he can only shave those who do not shave themselves. Therefore, if he shaves himself, he cannot shave himself, which leads to a contradiction.
    \item If the barber does not shave himself: In this case, since he shaves only those who do not shave themselves, it follows that he must shave himself. This again leads to a contradiction.
\end{enumerate}

Conclusion: In both scenarios—whether the barber shaves himself or does not shave himself—a contradiction arises. Thus, it is impossible for such a barber to exist without creating a logical inconsistency.

This paradox demonstrates the difficulties that can arise in set theory and self-reference, leading to contradictions similar to those found in Russell's paradox.
